Yes — keep the radio control **24×24**, but make the selected state a **dark-green filled circle with a small white center**.

Use this exact CSS:

```css
.sales-option input[type='radio'] {
    appearance: none;
    -webkit-appearance: none;

    width: 24px;
    height: 24px;
    flex: 0 0 24px;
    margin: 0;

    border: 1.5px solid #000000;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: #ffffff;

    position: relative;
    cursor: pointer;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

.sales-option input[type='radio']:checked {
    border-color: #154734;
    background-color: #154734;
}

.sales-option input[type='radio']:checked::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;

    width: 8px;
    height: 8px;
    top: 6.5px;
    left: 6.5px;

    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: #ffffff;
}
```

Because the radio is `24px` and border is `1.5px`, the inner usable area is around `21px`. An `8px` white dot centered at `6.5px` gives the expected look.

Also keep your label alignment like this:

```css
.sales-option {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 12px;

    font-family: 'Open Sans', Arial, sans-serif;
    font-weight: 300;
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 24px;
    color: #000000;
    cursor: pointer;
}
```

Remove any older `:checked::after` rule that uses `#6BDD00`; that bright green is for focus/border, not the selected radio center.
